LCM workflow plan-level dates ko merge karte waqt overwrite kar deta hai.



Isliye temporary access dates ko safely handle karne ke liye sunrise aur sunset ko AttributeRequest level pe lagao. kya samjhao hinglish me

Aapne SailPoint ka ek bahut hi advanced aur dukhne waali nass (pain point) ko pakda hai! Yeh dikkat aksar standard Provisioning lifecycle mein aati hai.

Aaiye isko ekdam aasan Hinglish mein, step-by-step samajhte hain ki is baat ka asli matlab kya hai, problem kya thi, aur solution kya hai.

1. Pehle samajhte hain Asli Problem (Overwrite Kyun Hota Hai?)
SailPoint mein jab aap kisi user ke liye access maangte hain, toh parde ke peeche ek ProvisioningPlan banta hai. Is plan ke andar do levels hote hain:

Plan-Level (Top Level): Poore plan ki main header information.

AttributeRequest Level (Item Level): Plan ke andar ki individual items (jaise Active Directory ka group, SAP ka role, wagera).

Gadbad kahan hoti hai?
Maan lijiye ek user ne ek hi time par do alag-alag roles ke liye request ki:

Role A: Iska access chahiye sirf 5 din ke liye (Temporary).

Role B: Iska access chahiye permanent (ya kisi alag date range ke liye).

Jab LCM Workflow chalta hai aur in dono requests ko ek bade plan mein Merge (इकट्ठा) karta hai, toh standard SailPoint engine ka ek behavior hota hai. Woh kya karta hai ki individual items ki dates ko dekhne ke bajay, Top-Level (Plan-Level) ki date se sabko overwrite (badal) deta hai.

Iska nateejah yeh hota hai ki Role A ki temporary dates ud jati hain, aur user ko dono roles galat dates ke sath mil jate hain.

2. Solution: Sunrise aur Sunset ko AttributeRequest Level pe lagao
Is problem se bachne ke liye statement mein yeh rasta bataya gaya hai: Dates ko poore plan par mat thopo, balki har ek item ke andar daalo.

SailPoint mein temporary access ke liye do keywords use hote hain:

sysSunrise (Start Date): Is din access automatic shuru (provision) hoga.

sysSunset (End Date): Is din access automatic khatam (deprovision) ho jayega.

Yeh kaam parde ke peeche kaise hota hai? (Developer Perspective)
Standard tarike mein dates yahan lagti thin (jo overwrite ho jati hain):

XML
<!-- GALAT TARIKA: Plan-Level Par (Yahan Overwrite ka khatra hai) -->
<ProvisioningPlan>
  <Attributes>
    <Map>
      <entry key="sysSunrise" value="2026-05-25"/>
      <entry key="sysSunset" value="2026-05-30"/>
    </Map>
  </Attributes>
  ...
</ProvisioningPlan>
Sahi aur safe tarika yeh hai ki dates ko AttributeRequest ke andar set kiya jaye (BeanShell ya Workflow rule ke zariye):

XML
<!-- SAHI TARIKA: AttributeRequest Level Par (Safely Handle) -->
<ProvisioningPlan>
  <AccountRequest application="Active Directory" op="Modify" nativeIdentity="cn=John Doe">
    
    <!-- Har ek individual group request ke andar date dalo -->
    <AttributeRequest name="memberOf" op="Add" value="CN=Finance-Team">
      <Attributes>
        <Map>
          <entry key="sysSunrise" value="2026-05-25"/> <!-- Is item ki apni shuruat date -->
          <entry key="sysSunset" value="2026-05-30"/>  <!-- Is item ki apni khatam date -->
        </Map>
      </Attributes>
    </AttributeRequest>

  </AccountRequest>
</ProvisioningPlan>
Summary (Ek chota example)
Ise aap aise samajhiye ki aap ek Courier Service (Plan) se do alag-alag packets bhej rahe hain.

Agar aapne poore bade dabbe (Plan-Level) par likh diya ki "Ise Monday ko deliver karna", toh andar ke dono packets Monday ko hi deliver honge.

Lekin agar aapne bade dabbe par kuch nahi likha, balki andar ke dono chote packets (AttributeRequest Level) par alag-alag slip chipkai ki "Packet 1 Monday ko do, aur Packet 2 Wednesday ko"—toh courier company unhe safely alag-alag din hi deliver karegi.

Isiliye, temporary access ki dates (sunrise/sunset) hamesha AttributeRequest level par lagayi jati hain taaki workflow aggregation ke waqt data lose na ho!

firse

Aaiye isko ekdam aasan bhasha mein firse samajhte hain. Yeh SailPoint ka ek aisa behavior hai jo kaafi developers ko shuruat mein pareshan karta hai.

Isko teen tukdon mein poori tarani saaf karte hain: Problem kya hai, engine kya galati karta hai, aur sahi rasta kya hai.

1. Plan-Level vs AttributeRequest Level (Sancha)
SailPoint mein jab koi access request aati hai, toh ek ProvisioningPlan banta hai. Iska structure ek sarkari form jaisa hota hai:

Plan-Level (Main Header): Yeh form ka sabse upar ka hissa hai (Bada Dabba).

AttributeRequest Level (Line Items): Yeh form ke andar ki tables ya lines hain jahan likha hota hai ki kaunsa group ya role chahiye (Chote Dabbe).

2. Overwrite Ki Asli Bimari (Problem)
Maan lijiye ek manager ne ek hi baar mein ek employee ke liye do alag-alag access maange:

Active Directory Group: Yeh sirf 10 din ke liye chahiye (Temporary).

SAP Application Role: Yeh hamesha ke liye chahiye (Permanent).

Jab SailPoint ka LCM Workflow in dono requests ko process karne ke liye ek bada plan banata hai aur unhe Merge (Aapas mein jodna) karta hai, toh engine ek bada ghumav leta hai.

Woh individual items ki alag-alag dates ko dhyan mein rakhne ke bajay, poore plan ke Header (Plan-Level) par jo main date range likhi hoti hai, use uthakar sab par thonp (overwrite) deta hai.

Iska nateeja yeh hota hai ki jo access aapne temporary maanga tha, uski date mity jati hai aur dono access permanent ya phir galat dates ke sath process ho jate hain.

3. Sunrise aur Sunset Ka Sahi Ilaaj (Solution)
SailPoint mein temporary access ko handle karne ke liye do attributes hote hain:

sysSunrise (Start Date): Is din access automatic active hoga.

sysSunset (End Date): Is din access automatic chhin (deprovision) jayega.

Statement kehta hai ki agar aapko is overwrite se bachna hai, toh in dono dates ko poore plan par mat lagao. Inhe seedhe AttributeRequest (yaani specific group ya role ke dabbe) ke andar daal do.

Sahi Code Ka Structure (XML Look):
