Aapne jin variables ko nikalal hai, yeh sab SailPoint IdentityIQ ke LCM (Lifecycle Manager) Framework ke Controlling Switches aur Standard Configuration Settings hain.

Aasan bhasha mein kahein toh yeh workflow ke "Steering Wheel" aur "Buttons" hain, jo yeh tay karte hain ki request kis raste se jayegi, kitni speed se chalegi, aur kahan rukegi.

Niche inka ek-ek line mein saaf matlab diya gaya hai:

1. Controlling Switches (Jo request ka rasta badalte hain)
endOnManualWorkItems: Agar access dene ke liye kisi insaan ko haath se (manual) kaam karna padne wala hai, toh kya workflow ko aage na badha kar wahin par khatam (end) kar dena chahiye? (Default false hota hai, yaani manual kaam hone tak workflow wait karta hai).

endOnProvisioningForms: Agar kisi application mein access dete waqt user ya manager ke samne koi extra form (input pop-up) aane wala hai, toh kya workflow ko wahin rok kar khatam kar dena chahiye? (Default false).

splitProvisioning: Yeh system ko batata hai ki kya chal rahi provisioning poore plan ka ek chota sa tukda (subset) hai, jise parallelly chalaya ja raha hai.

enableRetryRequest: Agar target application (jaise Active Directory) temporary down hai, toh kya workflow ko baar-baar try (retry) karna chahiye ya request ko error handle karne ke liye chod dena chahiye.

2. Performance aur Speed Settings (Parde ke peeche ya samne)
optimisticProvisioning: Agar ise true kar dein, toh SailPoint manager ke approve karte hi user ke profile (Identity Cube) par naya access turant dikhana shuru kar deta hai, bina target system se confirmation ka wait kiye.

foregroundProvisioning: Yeh speed badhane ka switch hai. Agar true hai, toh saari provisioning user ke samne (screen par load hote hue) turant hoti hai. Agar false ho, toh SailPoint use background thread mein daal deta hai taaki browser session hang na ho.

3. Integration aur Communication (Ticketing aur Email)
ticketManagementApplication: Agar aapki company ServiceNow ya Jira ka use karti hai ticketing ke liye, toh us ticketing tool ki application ka naam isme hota hai, taaki SailPoint wahan automatic ticket open/close kar sake.

LCM Requester Notification: Yeh us standard Email Template ka naam hai jo us insaan ko bheja jata hai jisne request lagayi hai (Requester), taaki use pata rahe ki uski request approve hui ya reject.

formTemplate: Jab user ko access diya ja raha ho aur koi form dikhana ho, toh us form ka standard look/design (Template) kaun sa hoga (jaise "Identity Update").

source: Yeh sirf ek tag (label) hai jo record mein likhta hai ki yeh request kahan se shuru hui thi. Standard LCM workflows mein isme hamesha "LCM" likha hota hai taaki auditing mein pehchanna aasan ho.

endOnManualWorkItems splitProvisioning

SailPoint IdentityIQ mein endOnManualWorkItems aur splitProvisioning dono hi workflow ka rasta aur behavior control karne wale do bahut hi advanced switches hain.

In dono ko ekdam simple shabdo mein aur real-life example ke sath samajhte hain:

1. endOnManualWorkItems (Insaan ke kaam karne par workflow ka rukna)
SailPoint mein do tarah se access diya jata hai:

Automated: SailPoint ne seedhe Active Directory se connect kiya aur user ka account bana diya (Bina kisi insaan ki madad ke).

Manual: Maan lijiye koi aisi purani application hai jiska SailPoint se direct connection nahi hai. Us case mein SailPoint ek Manual Work Item (Task) generate karta hai aur IT Helpdesk team ke kisi bande ko saunp deta hai ki "Bhai, tum haath se jaakar is user ka account banao."

Yeh switch kya karta hai?

false (Default): Workflow tab tak khatam nahi hoga jab tak woh Helpdesk ka banda haath se account banakar SailPoint mein "Complete" button nahi daba deta. Workflow wahin ruka rahega.

true: Jaise hi SailPoint ko pata chalta hai ki is request mein manual kaam ki zaroorat hai, woh Helpdesk ke liye ticket (Work Item) generate karega aur workflow ko turant wahin khatam (End) kar dega. Woh Helpdesk ke bande ke kaam poora karne ka wait nahi karega.

2. splitProvisioning (Bade kaam ko alag-alag thailiyo mein baantna)
Aapne pichle steps mein dekha tha ki jab ek user ek sath 3-4 applications ka access maangta hai, toh approvalSplitPoint unhe alag-alag tukdo (Sub-Plans) mein tod deta hai taaki alag-alag managers ek sath parallelly approve kar sakein.

Yeh switch kya karta hai?

Yeh ek Flag/Tag ki tarah hai jo niche chalne wale Identity Request Provision subprocess ko yeh batata hai ki: "Suno, abhi tumhare paas jo provisioning plan aaya hai, woh poora main request nahi hai. Woh ek bada request ka ek chota sa tukda (Subset/Split Part) hai, jise parallelly process kiya ja raha hai."

Ise true karne se SailPoint ka engine un chote-chote plans ko aapas mein mix nahi karta aur har ek split part ki provisioning ko safely aur independently handle karta hai.

Ek Simple Story Se Dono Ka Connection Samajhiye
Maan lijiye aapne Amazon se ek sath do cheezein order kiं: Ek Smartphone aur Ek Custom Hand-made Painting.

splitProvisioning ka kaam: Amazon ne aapke order ko do hisso mein baant diya (Split kar diya). Smartphone unke automatic warehouse se nikal raha hai, aur Painting ek artist haath se bana raha hai. Dono parallelly chal rahe hain.

endOnManualWorkItems ka kaam:

Smartphone automatic deliver ho gaya (Automated).

Painting ke liye ek artist ko haath se kaam karna padega (Manual Work Item).

Agar endOnManualWorkItems = false hai, toh Amazon aapka poora order tab tak "Open" rakhega jab tak painting banakar deliver nahi ho jaati.

Agar endOnManualWorkItems = true hai, toh Amazon painting ka kaam artist ko saunpते hi aapke main order status ko wahin close/end kar dega, aur painting ka kaam background mein chalta rahega.

