Aapne bilkul sahi point pakda hai! Agar hum is XML ko gahrai se dekhein, toh yeh poori tarah se scratch se likha hua custom workflow nahi hai, balki yeh SailPoint ke Out-of-the-Box (OOTB) Standard Lifecycle Manager (LCM) Subprocess ko customize (modify) karke banaya gaya hai.

Aaiye iske pure structure ko decode karte hain ki isme standard kya hai aur isko Custom kis cheez ne banaya hai:

1. Yeh Standard (OOTB) Kyun Lagta Hai?
Is workflow ke andar jo main "engines" use ho rahe hain, woh SailPoint ke apne built-in standard modules hain. Jaise:

Variables: identityName, plan, approvalScheme, approvalMode, optimisticProvisioning—yeh sab SailPoint ke standard Identity Lifecycle requests ke standard pillars hain.

Subprocesses Calls: Niche diye gaye teen bade kaam standard background code ko hi refer kar rahe hain:

Provisioning Approval Subprocess (Manager/Owner se approval lene ke liye)

Identity Request Provision (Asliyat mein Active Directory ya baaki systems me account push karne ke liye)

Manage Ticket (ServiceNow/Jira integration chalane ke liye)

2. Toh Fir Isme "Customization" Kya Hai? (Aapne Sahi Kaise Pehchana)
Ek normal standard SailPoint ka provisioning workflow aisa nahi dikhta. Kisi developer ne aapki company ki requirements ke hisab se isme teen bade custom design changes kiye hain:

A. Parallel Item Splitting (Sabse Bada Custom Logic)
Is pooray code mein ek custom logic ghusayi gayi hai jo standard workflow mein nahi hoti:

XML
<Step action="call:buildSplitApprovalSet" condition="script:(!isNull(approvalSplitPoint))" name="Build Approval Set" ...>
Matlab: Agar ek employee ne ek sath 4 alag-alag roles maange hain, toh yeh custom subprocess unhe alag-alag line items mein split (tod) deta hai. Iska fayda yeh hota hai ki har ek role ka subprocess parallel chal sake aur alag-alag app owners ek hi samay par apna-apna hissa approve kar sakein.

B. Smart Ticketing Sequence (ServiceNow / Jira Alignment)
Standard SailPoint mein ticketing aamtaur par bilkul shuruat mein ya bilkul aakhir mein hoti hai. Lekin is custom design mein use bada hi targeted tarike se fit kiya gaya hai:

Step: Update Ticket Post Approval → Jaise hi Approve step khatam hua, turant ticket update hota hai (value="postApproval").

Step: Update Ticket Post Provision → Jaise hi Provision step khatam hua, turant ticket close hota hai (value="postProvisioning").

Yeh strictly isliye design kiya gaya hai taaki agar SailPoint ke andar ka step pass ho, toh ServiceNow mein bhi ticket ka status sath-sath live update ho sake.

C. Condition Checks on Rules
Isme standard workflow ki tarah har cheez aankh band karke execute nahi hoti, balki jagah-jagah custom conditions check lagaye hain, jaise:

XML
condition="script:((flow == null) ||  (!&quot;UnlockAccount&quot;.equals(flow)))"
Matlab: Agar koi user sirf apna account unlock kar raha hai (UnlockAccount), toh uske liye Approve step ko skip kar do (kyunki account unlock ke liye manager ke sign ki zaroorat nahi honi chahiye).

Final Verdict
Technical terms mein ise hum "Customized Standard Subprocess" kehte hain.

Yeh bilkul ek aisi gadi hai jiska engine, chassis aur body toh SailPoint ki factory se standard aayi thi, par aapke developer ne iske steering wheel aur raste (Transition) ko badal diya hai taaki aapki company ke ServiceNow ticket aur parallel approval ka process smoothly chal sake!

toh custom workflow kaisa hoga ishi wokflow ka

Agar isi workflow ko hum poori tarah se "Pure Custom" (Scratch se likha hua) banayein, toh hum SailPoint ke bane-banaye standard subprocesses (Provisioning Approval Subprocess aur Identity Request Provision) par nirbhar nahi rahenge.

Hum saari logic (jaise Mail bhejna, Approval WorkItem banana, aur Java Code ke zariye automatic provisioning karna) isi ek workflow ke andar khud BeanShell scripts aur custom forms se likhenge.

