</Rule>

3.Account Invite Core Business Rule (Account Invite):-
Isko aapka Workflow Engine (WorkflowEngine) trigger karta hai.
Kaun trigger karta hai: SailPoint ka Workflow Executor (Internal Step Handler).
Kab trigger karta hai: Jab user form par details (Email aur Mobile) bhar kar "Submit" button daba deta hai 
aur workflow apne agle step par badhta hai.
Kaise chalta hai: Workflow ke andar aapne is step par explicit action likha hua hai: action="rule:Account Invite". 
Jaise hi workflow engine is step par pahunchta hai, woh is Rule ko call karta hai aur form ke saare inputs (email, mobile) 
is rule ke andar java variables ke roop mein inject kar deta hai taaki aapka backend business logic chal sake.
XML
<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<!DOCTYPE Rule PUBLIC "sailpoint.dtd" "sailpoint.dtd">
<Rule name="Account Invite" type="Workflow">
  <Description>Yeh rule workflow ke inputs lekar backend operation/API process chalaega.</Description>
  <Source>
    <![CDATA[
    import java.util.HashMap;
    import java.util.Map;
    import org.apache.commons.lang.StringUtils;

    Map response = new HashMap();
    int statusCode = 500; // Default failure

    // Workflow se inputs automatic is rule context me milenge
    if (email != null && mobile != null) {
        try {
            // ------ AAPKA BUSINESS LOGIC YAHAN AAYEGA ------
            // Jaise kisi external system ko REST API hit marna, ya user generate karna.
            
            System.out.println("Processing Account Invite for Email: " + email + " and Mobile: " + mobile);
            
            // Agar processing safal rahi:
            statusCode = 200; 
            
        } catch (Exception e) {
            System.out.println("Error while executing Account Invite Rule: " + e.getMessage());
            statusCode = 500;
        }
    }

    // Response map workflow ke resultVariable="response" me wapas chala jayega
    response.put("statusCode", statusCode);
    return response;
    ]]>
  </Source>
</Rule>
