Step 1: Ek Sundar Form Dikhata Hai (Display Form):-
Jaise hi user dashboard par button dabata hai, yeh workflow screen par ek form kholta hai aur do cheezein maangta hai:
Email Address
Mobile Number
Parde ke peeche ki smartness (Validation):-
Form par submit dabate hi yeh chupke se do security checks chalata hai:-
Email Check: Yeh dekhta hai ki domain sahi hai ya nahi (jaise @yourcompany.com). Agar kisi ne @gmail.com dala, toh yeh wahin rok dega.
Mobile Check: Yeh check karta hai ki number sahi format mein hai ya nahi (Singapore ka standard ^\+65-[89]\d{7}$ pattern check karta hai).

Step 2: Backend API/Logic Execute Karta Hai (Execute Rule):-
Jaise hi dono details sahi milti hain aur user "Submit" dabata hai, workflow aage badhkar Account Invite naam ke rule ko awaz lagata hai.
Yeh rule aapke form se email aur mobile ko uthata hai.
Real-world project mein yeh kisi external system ko REST API ke zariye hit maarta hai ya SailPoint ke andar hi ek temporary link generate karta hai.
Kaam hone ke baad yeh rule workflow ko ek status code lauta deta hai (jaise 200 matlab sab sahi raha, 500 matlab kuch gadbad hui).

Step 3: Screen Par Message Dikhata Hai (Confirmation step):-
Rule se status code milne ke baad yeh step user ke samne screen par ek popup message thonp deta hai:
Agar code 200 mila: "Account Invite sent successfully." (Green message)
Agar kuch aur mila: "Account Invite failed to send..." (Red error message)

()SailPoint IIQ mein do tarah ke workflows hote hain:-
-->Event-Driven Workflows (Auto-Pilot): Jaise Joiner, Mover, Leaver. Inme jab user ka data badalta hai, tab unhe chalane ke liye Lifecycle Event aur Trigger Rule lagta hai (jaise humne pichle cellphone wale example mein kiya tha).
-->Manual/Self-Service Workflows (QuickLink Tools): Yeh jo aapka "Account Invite" wala workflow hai, yeh tab chalta hai jab koi user khud dashboard par jaakar button par click karta hai.
Chunki yeh button click par chalta hai, isiliye isko chalane ka kaam direct QuickLink XML karta hai, na ki koi Lifecycle Event.
